### Typedef in C

The `typedef` keyword creates an alias (nickname) for an existing data type.

### Syntax

```c
typedef existing_type new_name;
```

### Examples

```c
typedef unsigned long ulong;
typedef struct Student Student;
typedef struct {
  int x;
  int y;
} Point;
```

### Benefits of Typedef

| Benefit | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Readability | `Student s1` vs `struct Student s1` |
| Portability | Abstract platform-specific types |
| Maintainability | Change underlying type in one place |
| Complex types | Simplify function pointer declarations |

### Common Typedef Patterns

```c
// Standard integer types
typedef unsigned char byte;

// Function pointer
typedef int (*Operation)(int, int);

// Structure without struct keyword
typedef struct {
  int id;
  char name[50];
} Employee;
```

---

> **Key Point:** Typedef does not create a new type, only an alias. Use it to improve code readability and portability.

codeExample:
#include <stdio.h>
typedef struct {
  int x;
  int y;
} Point;

typedef unsigned long long ULL;

int main() {
  Point p1 = {10, 20};
  ULL large = 1000000;
  printf("Point: (%d, %d)\n", p1.x, p1.y);
  printf("Large: %llu\n", large);
  return 0;
}
